snippet.textDisplay:
"if somebody clearly doesn't care, that's a different ball game"
How exactly does Steve know that's not the case with Ndombele? Because coming from a Spurs fan, while he's one of the most talented players I've seen at the club in a long while I haven't seen anything on the pitch to suggest he does care that much. It's not his fault he's been injured, but he doesn't look remotely bothered half the time, his work rate is shocking and it's not hard to think he might have an attitude problem.
I see nothing wrong with what Jose said. This is how he motivates his players, it's almost like a public challenge to the player to step up their game- he did it with Parrott too. He's trying to light a fire in Ndombele to make him realise his considerable potential, not start a hate campaign against him or 'throw him under the bus'. Half of what he said was about how talented a player Ndombele is and how he's got great things ahead of him if he takes the necessary steps. It's not like it's some kind of personal vendetta. When Ndombele makes positive steps, Jose will be the first to praise him, and publicly, like he's done with Lo Celso, Winks, Skipp, Dier, Alli, Bergwijn and others.
